  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Due diligence child labour herbs and spices supply chains</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Verstegen Spices &amp; Sauces, Epos Specerijen and Visser &amp; Zn, are conducting the project &#x2018;Due Diligence Child Labour Herbs &amp; Spices Supply Chains&#x2019;. The 3 companies are members of the Nederlandse Vereniging voor de Specerijenhandel (NVS) that intends to sign an IMVO covenant. Based on their most important spices and sourcing areas the three companies first want to generate insight into production regions where the risks of child labour in spices supply chains (at trading/processing and farm level) are the biggest: &#x2018;child labour hot spots.Secondly, together with local suppliers, NGOs and authorities they want to analyse root causes of child labour in maximum three &#x2018;pilot&#x2019; hot spots, including theoretical mitigating measures to address these.Furthermore, the feasibility of these theoretical measures will be assessed, both with regard to possibilities of measures &#x2018;on the ground&#x2019; and possibilities to take joint action with clients and 1st tier suppliers. In the fourth place current internal operational processes will be reviewed and if necessary adjusted (action plans for implementation will be developed). Such internal processes must ensure:(1) that no procedures are in place that unintendedly/indirectly contribute to child labour,(2) that child labour risks will be identified and mitigated structurally,(3) that achievements to eradicate child labour will be monitored periodically and(4) that there is structural internal and external transparency on child labour policies, achievements and bottlenecks.The three selected PCC pilots are Cumin in Turkey, Turmeric in India and Cardamom in Guatemala. Based on the lessons learned from this project a child labour tool kit will be developed that will be made available to other NVS members and other interested parties.</narrative>
  </description>
